{'content_type': 'audio_transcription', 'text': "Got it. You want to bridge the gap between Enlightenment-era emphasis on individualism and subjectivism, and a more relational or objective understanding of values. One way to do this is by highlighting how even Enlightenment thinkers valued rational discourse, shared human rights, and universal truths. By framing value realism in terms of a pursuit of universal principles that can be rationally understood and agreed upon, you can connect it to their commitment to reason and shared human experience.

A key angle might be to demonstrate how a relational understanding of values doesn't negate individual agency but rather enriches it by rooting it in a shared reality that transcends pure subjectivity. This could help bridge the gap and show that value realism offers a more holistic, interconnected perspective that Enlightenment thinkers could appreciate.

